segments.text: My name is Larry Probst.
I am a retired president of Betz Processed Chemicals here in the Woodlands.
I think one of the things that you are trying to determine is how Betz

and the probes family specifically got here to the woodlands let me back up just a little bit on my own personal history i was a 1950 graduate of villanova university as a chemical engineer and in june of 1950 i had a extremely interesting two weeks the 3rd of june my first son was born the 7th
was my first wedding anniversary.
The fifth, I graduated from Villanova.
And the 12th, I went to work for Betts Laboratories.
Since that time, I've had several responsibilities at Betts, moving through the engineering chairs to eventually become vice president of their engineering force.
And I also became a director in 1975

But in the latter part of 1977, Betts, which is a worldwide water and oil treating company, made the decision that they would have to move some of their analytical and research facilities from the Tribos area, which is a suburb just north of the city of Philadelphia,

and we chose to go somewhere in the south and since houston was the epicenter as we say of our business in this particular area it seemed quite natural to begin to look for space in this houston area i happen to be personally familiar with the woodlands having come here as an officer of bets
and the head of some of the units where we wanted to have regional meetings in this particular section.
And prior to coming to the Woodlands, we had been to places like April Sound and some others that I don't really recall right now in this area.
So when the Woodlands finally opened up their conference center, we came

very early in the game in the 76 77 period so when we decided in the november of 1977 to move south it was easy for me to think of the woodlands as a good place to locate my family one of the reasons why i felt comfortable in the woodlands bringing my wife and
16-year-old daughter was the fact that my son, Thomas, already lived here.
He was a contract painter working for some of our original builders here, such as Tom Cox and Jim O'Connor, and some of the others that may not necessarily still be building here.
But anyhow, Tom and his wife, Sue, had moved here in the latter 76.

So knowing that I would have to do a good bit of traveling and not wanting my wife and daughter to feel too alone, I thought that the Woodlands would be an excellent place for them to be living with the closeness of Tom and his family.
After we decided where we would locate,
We then began to look around the Houston area for a suitable spot of 15 or 20 acres of land.
And we realized that in order to have a campus-like atmosphere, similar to the ones we had in the Philadelphia area, we couldn't locate in areas like Rankin Road or off of 45 or off of 59.
So we shopped.
and finally settled on the two places where we could locate Kingwood and the Woodlands.
One of the things you mentioned earlier, which I thought might be significant, is the issue of the covenant.
That's what I was getting to.
The Kingwood area and the Woodlands area both
gave us easy access to the international airport.
And since I personally had already decided and made commitments to build a house, I was leaning towards the woodlands.
But one of the other executives of bets was responsible for picking the location.
And coincidentally, he ended up coming here
with one of the early real estate persons, and I can't recall his name right offhand.
But after he looked the two places over, he felt that the Woodlands was a better location and proceeded to spend about a half an hour on the telephone convincing me
halfway across the country that this was a good spot.
We both realized that the restrictive covenants that the Woodlands had was one of the main features for our laboratory and research and headquarters for the Betz Process Chemical Company.
I think those features

are probably the main reasons why we located here in addition to the general quality of this area as compared to living in the champions area or naturally any of us that wanted to be part of the vets campus and our homes if we could do them in the same area why
It would be far better for us than doing like we just did in Philadelphia, drive 15 to 20 miles every day to work.
You actually discussed that on the phone then, the advantages of being able to live in the area where you were working.
Well, that was one of the main things that we used to sell the other people that we were bringing from other parts of the country.
We brought research and laboratory people from Philadelphia, but we brought salesmen, managers,
and other high-tech people from other parts of the United States, such as California, Chicago area, some in the central Midwest, in St. Louis, Denver.
There were perhaps 25 people that were the original cadre of the vets group here.

we made arrangements with the woodlands and bought 20 acres in the location that we are now and after we did that we of course cleared the land and built our first 40 000 square foot building in the shape of a t with the top half of the t the headquarters for
That's Process Chemical Company, and then the bottom half were the Analytical Laboratory and the research.
Subsequent to that, we built about another 55,000 square feet of research space as we expanded about two years after opening there in 1980.
recommended to people as they were considered to transfer from Philadelphia to the woodlands operation.
It was relatively easy to convince them to come to the south in addition to the good climate compared to all the snow digging that we had to do.

wonderful area of the woodlands and the new hometown program and everything else the growth pattern the hike and bike trails i often say that coming here at 52 i regret i didn't come here at the age of 32 and raise my family here rather than having most all of them out of high school by the time i got here because all of the younger generation of feds that has come here

used to always go back to Philadelphia and tell the people back there that it was like a constant vacation while they lived in the woodlands with all of the programs that we had here for the children, with the swimming pools and the facilities that we had.
And of course, when we came here, there were only 3,000 people and no red lights.
Now we have about 30,000 and a lot of red lights.
We only had the original village of Grogan's Mill at the time, and only the two golf courses, but a lot of tennis courts and a lot of opportunities for all ages of people.
That's fine.
One of the things, has Betts been
in a growth mode since you came?
Have new staff members or researchers come since then?
Has that initial sense of enamor with the woodlands maintained itself through?
I would say so, yes, because we've had people come here almost on a continuous basis for the first seven or eight years, from 1978 until about the past two years.
where we would bring different units of best research, maybe just four or five people.
And then another year would pass, and we'd bring four or five more and maybe hire some.
Most of the technicians are hired locally.
Most of the research managers have transferred from Philadelphia or from some other part of the country.
But I know that when they were hiring people to come here,
to identify and show them all the advantages that we had here at the Woodlands helped a lot of people to make up their mind to move from other parts that were not quite as enjoyable to live and work.
One thing in the very early stages, we all talked about having the University of Houston campus here.
And that brought a few people.
to this area to help increase their education.
And that did not develop into an active program.
They since have gone to some of the other local schools in order to get their extra degrees.
How active was the Woodmans itself?
in helping you as a director locate these people here?
Did they play a role, a significant role?
Were they supportive?
I would say that not only the Woodlands people, but also some of the other Houston area groups that helped people transfer from other parts of the country to this particular area.
There were a lot of real estate
and development people that had units.
I think one of them at the time was called the Woodlands Development Council or something like that.
I really don't remember.
But there were several different people that I remember helped us.
One of the original men that's still here is a chap by the name of Rex Johnson, who was primarily responsible for us finally deciding on where we located and
the exact acreage that we picked, because we had two or three choices.
None of this area north of Timberlock was developed at that time.
So we had to literally build the roads to get to our location.
So it was a little difficult to visualize what it was going to be like.
And of course, with other people like Richard Brown
Ed Lee, who was the original president.
Those are just some of the few people that I can remember at the beginning.
Let me just say one more thing about our family.

indicate how totally convenient it is to live in the woodlands in my opinion we had of course as i said earlier our son thomas lived here before we came and when my wife and my daughter gina came down in 78 then within two years after that my son michael joined us and stayed with us for about a year and then married and now he lives here so i have one of the
A few people with three generations, two sons and three grandchildren.
This really is a hometown.
And this is obvious.

And when people ask me if I were going back to Philadelphia when I retired this year from Betts after 40-plus years, having passed the retirement age of 65, I was asked, oh, I'm sure you and your wife will return to Philly.
And the answer was no.

very simply, no, there's no reason that we should ever consider going back to Philly because we have our two sons and three grandchildren here, and we have our daughter and her husband living in Austin after she subsequently went to University of Texas and graduated from there.
So they're living in Austin, and now they're expecting a baby, so the remaining, our oldest boy and his two children and his wife live in
San Francisco area in Black Hawk, south of Walnut Creek.
And we just came back from there.
And since my wife and I do travel a lot, we had no problem going out to California.
I returned to Philadelphia about every month or nine or 10 times a year for our vets board meetings.
So I'll continue to do that until April of 92.

And to then talk about the pavilion, one of the other responsibilities that I had here or one of the avocations early was a member of the board of directors of the original bank in the Woodlands, which eventually became M Bank of Woodlands.
And it's now Bank One, but when the Bank One people took over MBank, well, they dissolved all of the boards, so you no longer have a board.
But I think the opportunity to work in the community, and of course I also am the head of the Finance Committee of St. Simon and Jude Catholic Church.
It seems to me that some of the older and earlier people here were assigned some of the...
responsibilities from the different organizations and churches, so I'm sure that's why I ended up doing some of the other than vets business.
And I'm also a member of the Houston Golf Association, so I've got many things to keep me busy in my retirement.
And one of the opportunities I was given towards the end of
well, I should say in the early part of 1990, was the opportunity to be on the board of the Pavilion, Cynthia Woods Mitchell Pavilion for the Performing Arts.
Some people have indicated that I got the job because the Betz parking lot was right near the pavilion, but I don't like to think that was the whole reason.
But having known
the Mitchells as well as the other people in the hierarchy of the Mitchell organization.
I'm sure that my name was one of the ones on the list of candidates for the board members.
And that gave me an opportunity to, again, have something else to work with during my retirement.
I think that the pavilion is probably going to be one of the nicest units of the woodlands.
We've only completed one year, but we have a lot of plans for 1991 to increase the number of programs.
And I'm sure that the opportunity to provide more cultural
involvements for the people in the Woodlands will make this hometown a bigger and even better hometown.
Do you have a sense of how many people from the Woodlands have attended program versus how many from surrounding communities?
No, they've taken surveys of the people that have come to the

programs but i think it's very difficult i know from talking to many of my friends in the woodlands that all of the industries have sent people from their companies as part of perks for their own employees for example at vets we had a box and also we had four reserve seats
And if we did not have customers that were able to come and join up with us at any of the performances, why, we would then turn the tickets over to our employees and their families so that
Was that a bed suggestion or did that come from folks in the woodlands?
No, that was our own decision.
But other companies are doing the same thing?
But we know that other companies have been doing the same thing, especially those people that are in adjacent boxes to us.
We've noticed that they've been sending their employees as well as their own customers.
And I know from talking to the younger generation, you know, my son's associates, both my boys have different

groups that they associate with in their sporting events, you know, the tennis and golf and softball and, of course, all of the younger generation with the soccer teams and the independent football and baseball, little league, all of those fathers that are one generation away from me, they all have these opportunities in the Woodlands to be involved in all these
athletic events.
And now I even have some of my grandchildren getting involved in those.
But getting back to the pavilion, I know that there are a lot of people that have sent the younger folks to the pavilion.
A lot of them have gone on their own to the various performances that we've had.
Because my generation doesn't really know all of those performances.
But my son's generation knew them all by heart, and they were always participating in the shows.
What has been the philosophical or the values that the board has utilized or seen demonstrated in the Pavilion?
To what audience is it aiming its venue of acts?
Well, I think that one of the things that we're trying to do right now is to focus more on the type of programs that we're going to have.
Thirty, for example, in number for what I call the non-performing arts or the musical units, such as Crosby, Stills, and Nash, you know, those, however you define those, whether it's rock or
concert or whatever, and then we're going to have twenty or more of the cultural things such as the ballet and the symphony and that type.
So I would say that we're trying to focus on every generation and every type of
cultural program that most anybody would be interested in.
So is it abroad?
You're trying to get all generations.
Obviously you can get the older people with some of the pop arts.
Last year when you had Frank Sinatra and some of those older people.
The Woodlands does not have a high percentage of over 50.
Because every company that came here had maybe a manager over 50 and then several 40 year olds.
So we don't have a standard

town of age brackets because we are almost in a pyramid form with a few olders and then a few more in the 40s and a lot more in the 30s and a tremendous number in the 20s so the people that move here with companies normally came in in that type of as i call it pyramid form but there have been a number of people that have moved here
for retirement that I'm familiar with from my older golf partners.
They had 40 or 50-year-old children here that came as part of a company.
So then when they came here and visited, they found what a nice place it was to locate.
And if you can get through July and August in the summer, most Yankees can stand the South.
And so I know quite a few people that have retired here.
Paul Womack said he doesn't even go on vacations anymore.
He can't think of any place he wants to go.
Everything that he wants to do is right here.
While that may be a little bit extreme, I think it's illustrative of what you're saying.
It's a pleasant place for people.
Well, we used to laugh about people who came down here of our original group back in 78.

when they would go back to Philadelphia to visit their relatives at Christmas time or weddings or whatever, the comment was always made that living in the woodlands was like being on a constant vacation.
And more than one family expressed that back to our Philadelphia people.
So the statement was made in our internal group at Betts that
Maybe those folks down in the woodlands are really not working as hard as they should be.
Everybody always came back.
Everybody came back north with a good suntan.
And one hand is always more tan than the other from the golf gloves.
So the snow diggers...

always did envious and then of course when they used to come down here for we had quarterly meetings of our executive staff that came here uh maybe a group of anywhere from six to ten people including our chief financial officer our chief legal officer the chairman the president and several others ahead of our research department those people came

and reviewed with us our work program for our vets process company and our vets energy company in california secondary recovery work and when they would come they would stay two or three days and naturally they were very impressed number one with the woodlands in with the facilities that we had here the glass menagerie for our big formal suppers

uh places like the feed store or quick barbecue lunches and heidens for the seafood we always seem to have so many things around here that we could take everybody to and i've always made the statement that the beauty of the woodlands is that everything is five minutes away you can go to church you can go to the barbers you can get your shoes fixed you can get your cleaning post office
a reasonable number of small shops for your wife.
And the vets and the doctors and just everything that you need is all done.
We who lived in Philadelphia had to travel anywhere from 30 to 45 or 60 minutes to get to the pediatrician, to get to the hospital that you prefer to have your children at,
Facilities for, obviously, any kind of a cultural facility had to be cleared downtown in Philadelphia to get to the airport within an hour.
And whenever it snowed, then it was twice that.
And our offices were anywhere from 30 to 60 minutes away, depending upon the weather, so that the ability to do everything in five minutes
It's just a miracle, as far as I'm concerned, from a work and a living standpoint.
That was my big theme all the years I've been here, that everything is five minutes away.
That's a good testimonial of what Mr. Mitchell was trying to do.
One last question, because I haven't had anybody else to ask this, and you brought it to my mind since you're obviously an avid golfer.
Tell me about golf in the Woodlands.
Are they got four courses now?
When we came, the

original course that was wrapped around the conference center was known as the west course and the east course was just being completed in 78 and that's the one that's now the tournament players course where they had the houston open they had the houston open for a few years on the west course and eventually the west was added to

in two areas nine more holes added to the original and first the left side and then the right side or the north side i guess you'd call it over in panther creek and that became the north golf course and then of course the west new nine holes were over in the grogan's mill area grogan's point rather than grogan's mill then the fourth course is the arnold palmer course which is
way out on the west side in one of the other villages.
See, when we came here, the original concept was something like six or seven individual villages, all with separate shopping, separate living, separate everything, separate intermediate schools.
And the first one was the only one that existed in 78, that's Grogan's Mill.
Now they have the ones in Panther Creek and Cochran's Crossing.
And I forget right now.
The newer ones over on the other side.
And of course, the lake was built way after.
And the reason we selected our location
right there on the corner of Brogan's Mill and what will eventually be Lake Woodlands Drive.
We will be on one of the major intersections.
And I'll never forget one of the chairman's concerns was that we were located too close to the fire house and the police station.
He said you may eventually end up with so much noise that it may not be a good spot.
But with the way everything is built in the woodlands, with the trees and the setback theory of buildings, it's never been a problem.
Surely you can hear it, but it's never been that much of a problem.
So it's not an annoyance.
The insulation of all the trees and the and so forth really makes it
It's a great place.
Well, is there anything I should ask you to have it?
I can't think of anything right now.
